<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06214113 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06214113 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PENINSULA; HOUSING; DEVELOPMENT; ENVIRONMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  City officials have been known to demand some pretty unusual things fromdevelopers eager to build in their community. But allowing landslides to occurand fires to burn, all to protect butterflies?;    Those are some of theconditions Brisbane officials have set down in a drive to protect the MissionBlue Butterfly and native plant population of the San Bruno mountain range.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  UNUSUAL CONDITIONS ATTACHEDFOR BUTTERFLY'S SAKE, FIRES MAY BURN, LANDMAY SLIDE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related story on page 1B of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Small ground fires and landslides have been found to help the survival ofthe rare butterfly, which developers of the 578-home project in the mountainarea have agreed to help preserve.;    So along with building the homes, thedeveloper must also erect special retaining walls that make it possible forlandslides to occur naturally without damaging either the housing or theroads, said Brisbane Planning Director Carole Nelson.;    What's more, planscall for the installation of a complex irrigation system for some of the landadjacent to the homes. The system will spray water on the area after officialsset it on fire from time to time, she said. High-tech sensors will be used todetermine when the sprinklers should go on.;    And to make sure the firesdon't get out of control, special wet flora that won't overrun the nativeplants should be used for landscaping nearby.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  SHELBY GRAD, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910801  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  222  </WORD.CT>